  "text": "The Rust compiler's type inference engine is composed of three core components:\n\n1. **InferCtxt** (compiler/rustc_infer/src/infer/mod.rs, line 231): The main inference context struct that manages the global type inference state. It contains a TyCtxt reference, manages typing modes, region constraints, trait selection caches, and evaluation caches. This is the central hub for all type inference operations during compilation.\n\n2. **FnCtxt** (compiler/rustc_hir_typeck/src/fn_ctxt/mod.rs, line 44): The function-level type checker that implements type inference at the function scope. It holds references to the InferCtxt, maintains parameter environments, tracks return type coercions, and manages control flow divergence. FnCtxt is created fresh for each function and provides the primary interface for HIR-level type checking.\n\n3. **TypeVariableOrigin** (compiler/rustc_infer/src/infer/type_variable.rs, line 94): A struct that tracks the origin of type variables created during inference. It stores a Span (source location) and an optional param_def_id (the type parameter it was instantiated for). This metadata is crucial for diagnostics and understanding where inference variables came from.\n\nThese three components work together: InferCtxt provides the overall inference machinery, FnCtxt applies it to individual functions, and TypeVariableOrigin tracks the creation and origins of type variables throughout the inference process."
}

